<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
    <a href="/backlog/2158-package-fui-component-render-so-we-builds-single-repo/">#2158</a> asks how WE's
    docs site gets FUI's <strong>component-render</strong> build tool without the cross-repo sibling checkout —
    so a fresh clone, GitHub Actions, or <strong>Cloudflare Workers Builds</strong> (single-repo only) can
    build. Today WE's eleventy build <strong>subprocess-execs</strong> the FUI CLI at
    <code>we:../frontierui/dist/tools/component-render/cli.mjs</code> — deliberately an exec, never an import,
    because a build-time <code>import '@frontierui'</code> is the <em>one</em> thing that violates the ratified
    WE&harr;FUI boundary (<code>we:docs/agent/platform-decisions.md:224-226</code>).
</p>

<h2>The load-bearing correction</h2>
<p>
    The item's premise "WE already consumes <code>@frontierui/*</code> as packages" is <strong>false</strong> —
    they are vite/tsconfig <em>sibling-source aliases</em>, and FUI publishes nothing to npm (the
    <code>@frontierui</code> scope is held "restricted until an explicit go"). And the built
    <code>cli.mjs</code> is <strong>not self-contained</strong>: <code>fui:scripts/build-tools.mjs:56</code>
    bundles <code>packages:'external'</code>, so <code>happy-dom</code> (+ transitive
    <code>iconv-lite</code>/<code>safer-buffer</code>) is resolved at runtime from <code>node_modules</code>.
    Vendoring one file therefore also needs happy-dom in WE's tree — resolved against <strong>WE's lockfile,
    not FUI's</strong> — which silently retargets the #1867 reproducibility invariant ("invoked from within the
    FUI checkout against FUI's locked lockfile", <code>:1503-1505</code>) and risks cross-repo SSR render-skew.
</p>

<h2>Recommendation (to ratify in #2158)</h2>
<ol>
    <li><strong>End-state: npm-publish <code>@frontierui/component-render</code>.</strong> The only option that
        <em>dissolves</em> the happy-dom coupling (a published package declares happy-dom as its own dependency,
        npm-resolved reproducibly) — but gated behind the held-scope governance "go" + a new publish pipeline,
        so it cannot be the <em>now</em> answer.</li>
    <li><strong>Interim (now): vendor the prebuilt CLI, execed as today, correctly pinned.</strong> The pin is
        the built artifact <em>+ the exact happy-dom / transitive versions + a WE-lockfile constraint matching
        FUI's</em> (not a bare commit hash), and <code>codifiedIn</code> must <strong>amend the #1867 anchor's
        "from within the FUI checkout" clause</strong>. This <em>removes the FUI read from the deploy path</em>
        (a fresh clone builds; the credential survives only in one scheduled sync job that runs the existing
        <code>EXPECTED_PRODUCER</code> pin-check) — it does not "drop the PAT" outright.</li>
    <li><strong>Rejected:</strong> sibling checkout (status quo); git submodule / GH-release-fetch (still need a
        private-repo read credential, don't unlock Workers Builds); committing FUI tool <em>source</em> and
        building it in WE (a zero-impl / memory-rule-#6 violation). The vendored <em>exec'd</em> artifact is a
        build cache, not WE-authored impl — boundary-safe.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Method</h2>
<p>
    Skeptic pass <strong>SURVIVES-WITH-AMENDMENT</strong> (refuted the "self-contained artifact" premise;
    folded in the happy-dom pin + the #1867 amendment); fresh-context screen <strong>CLEAR</strong>. Full
    grounding, with verified <code>file:line</code> citations, in
    <code>we:reports/2026-07-09-single-repo-docs-build-fui-tool-distribution.md</code>.
</p>
